o notice how what the other person wants can reveal more than loud claims, since incentives usually show up in patterns of behavior.","The chapter treats persuasion and respect as a real balancing act, not a slogan, and it warns that pushing one side too far creates new vulnerabilities.","Instead of glorifying force or charisma, the material frames progress as the result of patient positioning, careful observation, and timely action.","A central lesson is that people around you respond to incentives, status, and perceived fairness, so your approach has to account for those forces.","The chapter highlights arguing for your goal instead of theirs as a recurring mistake, especially for students and early career people who confuse intensity with leverage."],"takeaways":["interest based motivation","increase willingness","what the other person wants","persuasion and respect","arguing for your goal instead of theirs","respect without manipulation"],"practice":["Write the decision goal before you act","Name the incentive each side is responding to","Notice one signal that matters more than words","Check where arguing for your goal instead of theirs could distort your judgment"]},"medium":{"summaryBullets":["Speak to What Others Want asks the reader to see interest based motivation as a deliberate choice rather than a personality trait or lucky break.","The chapter argues that strong outcomes usually begin with a clearer reading of increase willingness, because vague aims create waste and overreaction.","A repeated theme is that self focused persuasion often looks attractive in the short term, yet it weakens judgment when conditions become tense or uncertain.","The reader is pushed to notice how what the other person wants can reveal more than loud claims, since incentives usually show up in patterns of behavior.","The chapter treats persuasion and respect as a real balancing act, not a slogan, and it warns that pushing one side too far creates new vulnerabilities.","Instea