 where treating people as interchangeable could distort your judgment","Choose a response that protects legitimacy","Review the tradeoff before making a public move"]},"hard":{"summaryBullets":["Names Build Recognition asks the reader to see personal recognition as a deliberate choice rather than a personality trait or lucky break.","The chapter argues that strong outcomes usually begin with a clearer reading of make people feel seen, because vague aims create waste and overreaction.","A repeated theme is that generic treatment often looks attractive in the short term, yet it weakens judgment when conditions become tense or uncertain.","The reader is pushed to notice how the response to being remembered can reveal more than loud claims, since incentives usually show up in patterns of behavior.","The chapter treats recognition and familiarity as a real balancing act, not a slogan, and it warns that pushing one side too far creates new vulnerabilities.","Instead of glorifying force or charisma, the material frames progress as the result of patient positioning, careful observation, and timely action.","A central lesson is that people around you respond to incentives, status, and perceived fairness, so your approach has to account for those forces.","The chapter highlights treating people as interchangeable as a recurring mistake, especially for students and early career people who confuse intensity with leverage.","Name memory becomes useful because it trains the reader to slow down and choose the next move with more intention.","The text emphasizes that trust and reputation are cumulative, meaning one impulsive win can undermine the long game if it damages legitimacy.","There is a strong distinction between reacting to appearances and understanding structure, because surface confidence often hides weak preparation.","The chapter argues that pressure should clarify priorities, not scramble them, and the best operators reduce noise before they escalate effort.","Another theme is that alliances, norms, and narratives shape outcomes as much as raw ability, especially inside schools, teams, and workplaces.","The reader is asked to think in terms of second order effects, asking what today’s move teaches others about your standards and intent.","Ethically, the chapter draws a line between strategic awareness and empty manipulation, stressing that durable influence depends on legitimacy.","By the end, relationship judgment is presented as a discipline of reading context well, acting with restraint, and preserving room for future moves."],"takeaways":["personal recognition","make people feel seen","the response to being remembered","recognition and familiarity","treating people as interchangeable","respect without manipulation","make people feel seen","recognition"],"practice":["Write the decision goal before you act","Name the incentive each side is responding to","Notice one signal that matters more than words","Check where treating people as interchangeable could distort your judgment","Choose a response that protects legitimacy","Review the tradeoff before making a public move","Ask what future behavior your choice will encourage","Keep a short note on what you learned from the outcome"]}},"examples":[{"exampleId":"ch06-ex01","title":"Friend tension","contexts":["personal"],"scenario":"A friend group starts drifting into small status games and mixed signals. You notice that people are reacting to the response to being remembered more than what anyone says directly, and the whole situation feels harder to read because everyone is trying to protect face at the same time.","whatToDo":["Use the chapter idea of personal recognition by slowing the situation down, naming the actual goal, and responding in a way that protects the relationship while still dealing with the issue. Keep your move clear, proportionate, and consistent with the kind of reputation you want over time."],"whyItMatters":"Personal conflict in your twenties often gets wo