tall because nobody wants to say what the real problem is. Some people are protecting their image, others are avoiding work, and the team keeps circling around the task without naming the incentives that are driving the behavior.","whatToDo":["Use perspective taking to make the goal visible, separate roles from ego, and structure the next decision around clear accountability. Keep the discussion on outcomes and signals rather than turning it into a personal debate about who cares more."],"whyItMatters":"School environments train people to perform competence, but performance can crowd out honest coordination. This example matters because it shows how better strategic framing can make a team fairer and more effective at the same time."},{"exampleId":"ch17-ex04","title":"Club leadership choice","contexts":["school"],"scenario":"You are helping run a campus club and a visible conflict breaks out over direction, credit, and who gets to speak for the group. The chapter theme matters because the wrong public move could damage trust and make future coordination much harder.","whatToDo":["Read the room through the lens of reduce status threat, decide what needs to be protected first, and choose a response that lowers noise while preserving legitimacy. Focus on incentives, role clarity, and the long term health of the group rather than a fast symbolic win."],"whyItMatters":"Campus leadership often feels informal, but reputations form quickly and can shape opportunities for years. This example matters because it shows how strategic discipline can keep a community functional without rewarding ego or confusion."},{"exampleId":"ch17-ex05","title":"Internship pressure","contexts":["work"],"scenario":"At an internship or first job, you are asked to handle a tense situation where the obvious move might calm the room now but create a worse incentive later. The chapter’s warning about assuming intent without checking becomes practical because you do not have unlimited authority or room for error.","whatToDo":["Apply the chapter by clarifying the real objective, noticing where incentives are misaligned, and making a move that protects both trust and future options. Communicate with calm precision so your decision feels intentional rather than reactive."],"whyItMatters":"Early career people are often judged not just on results but on how they think under pressure. This scenario matters because it turns the chapter into a workplace habit, showing how better judgment can build credibility before you have formal power."},{"exampleId":"ch17-ex06","title":"Team messaging","contexts":["work"],"scenario":"A team is about to send a strong message to a client, manager, or partner, but the internal discussion is split between sounding tough and sounding cooperative. The deeper issue is not wording alone. It is what the message signals about standards, leverage, and future expectations.","whatToDo":["Use the chapter idea of how they describe the situation to choose language that is firm, clear, and aligned with the outcome you actually want. Make sure the message sets the right incentive structure and does not create unnecessary contempt, confusion, or escalation."],"whyItMatters":"A lot of workplace influence comes from signals that travel beyond the immediate conversation. This example matters because it shows that communication is strategic design, not just expression, and that a good move should strengthen both results and legitimacy."}],"quiz":{"passingScorePercent":80,"questions":[{"questionId":"ch17-h-q01","prompt":"According to this chapter, what is the best starting point for using perspective taking well?","choices":["Escalating quickly so people take you seriously","Clarifying the real goal and reading the context carefully","Copying the strongest voice in the room","Trusting first impressions over patterns"],"correctIndex":1},{"questionId":"ch17-h-q02","prompt":"Why does the chapter warn against mind reading?","choices":["Because it creates fast 