der effects?","choices":["Because future incentives and expectations are shaped by today’s move","Because every action should be delayed","Because only symbolic gestures matter","Because outcomes are mostly random"],"correctIndex":0},{"questionId":"ch19-h-q08","prompt":"What ethical line does the chapter try to maintain?","choices":["That strategic awareness should still preserve legitimacy rather than reward empty manipulation","That power always justifies the method","That conflict is resolved best by hiding intentions completely","That fairness matters only when you are already winning"],"correctIndex":0},{"questionId":"ch19-h-q09","prompt":"If someone wanted to apply this chapter in school or work, what habit would fit the summary best?","choices":["Making louder arguments before understanding incentives","Defining the goal, reading the signals, and choosing a proportionate move","Avoiding any decision until conditions are perfect","Copying a tactic without checking the context"],"correctIndex":1},{"questionId":"ch19-h-q10","prompt":"What is the deepest lesson of the chapter for someone in their twenties?","choices":["That pressure should push you to look stronger than you feel","That good judgment comes from reading structure, managing tradeoffs, and acting with restraint","That relationships matter less than leverage","That success mostly depends on being naturally dominant"],"correctIndex":1}]}},{"chapterId":"ch20-make-ideas-vivid","number":20,"title":"Make Ideas Vivid","readingTimeMinutes":13,"contentVariants":{"easy":{"summaryBullets":["Make Ideas Vivid asks the reader to see vivid communication as a deliberate choice rather than a personality trait or lucky break.","The chapter argues that strong outcomes usually begin with a clearer reading of improve memorability, because vague aims create waste and overreaction.","A repeated theme is that flat explanation often looks attractive in the short term, yet it weakens judgment when conditions become tense or u