table behavior.","whatToDo":["Apply the chapter by paying closer attention to repeated patterns, not isolated gestures. Look for whether words, incentives, and follow through line up, and choose a pace that gives you enough information to protect your standards without becoming cynical."],"whyItMatters":"A lot of personal regret comes from making large decisions while reading only mood and appearance. This scenario matters because it shows how strategic thinking can stay ethical and grounded, helping you build healthier relationships instead of reacting to intensity alone."},{"exampleId":"ch20-ex03","title":"Group project friction","contexts":["school"],"scenario":"A group project begins to stall because nobody wants to say what the real problem is. Some people are protecting their image, others are avoiding work, and the team keeps circling around the task without naming the incentives that are driving the behavior.","whatToDo":["Use vivid communication to make the goal visible, separate roles from ego, and structure the next decision around clear accountability. Keep the discussion on outcomes and signals rather than turning it into a personal debate about who cares more."],"whyItMatters":"School environments train people to perform competence, but performance can crowd out honest coordination. This example matters because it shows how better strategic framing can make a team fairer and more effective at the same time."},{"exampleId":"ch20-ex04","title":"Club leadership choice","contexts":["school"],"scenario":"You are helping run a campus club and a visible conflict breaks out over direction, credit, and who gets to speak for the group. The chapter theme matters because the wrong public move could damage trust and make future coordination much harder.","whatToDo":["Read the room through the lens of improve memorability, decide what needs to be protected first, and choose a response that lowers noise while preserving legitimacy. Focus on incentives, role clarity, 