:["Status symbols","which moments are face sensitive","Optimistic promises","Immediate emotional reactions"],"correctIndex":1},{"questionId":"ch26-h-q04","prompt":"How does the chapter describe correction and dignity?","choices":["As a slogan that works in every situation","As a balancing problem that creates new risks when pushed too far","As a matter of personal style only","As a reason to avoid hard choices entirely"],"correctIndex":1},{"questionId":"ch26-h-q05","prompt":"Which mistake is most closely tied to destroying face in front of others in the summary?","choices":["Mistaking intensity for leverage and reacting without structure","Giving people too much written detail","Waiting for more information than you need","Using a clear plan before acting"],"correctIndex":0},{"questionId":"ch26-h-q06","prompt":"What is the chapter’s view of trust and reputation?","choices":["They matter only after formal power is secured","They are mostly cosmetic compared with raw force","They are cumulative assets that can be damaged by careless short term wins","They can be repaired instantly with stronger messaging"],"correctIndex":2},{"questionId":"ch26-h-q07","prompt":"Why does the chapter emphasize second order effects?","choices":["Because future incentives and expectations are shaped by today’s move","Because every action should be delayed","Because only symbolic gestures matter","Because outcomes are mostly random"],"correctIndex":0},{"questionId":"ch26-h-q08","prompt":"What ethical line does the chapter try to maintain?","choices":["That strategic awareness should still preserve legitimacy rather than reward empty manipulation","That power always justifies the method","That conflict is resolved best by hiding intentions completely","That fairness matters only when you are already winning"],"correctIndex":0},{"questionId":"ch26-h-q09","prompt":"If someone wanted to apply this chapter in school or work, what habit would fit the summary best?","choices":["Making louder arguments before understanding incentives","Defining the goal, reading the signals, and choosing a proportionate move","Avoiding any decision until conditions are perfect","Copying a tactic without checking the context"],"correctIndex":1},{"questionId":"ch26-h-q10","prompt":"What is the deepest lesson of the chapter for someone in their twenties?","choices":["That pressure should push you to look stronger than you feel","That good judgment comes from reading structure, managing tradeoffs, and acting with restraint","That relationships matter less than leverage","That success mostly depends on being naturally dominant"],"correctIndex":1}]}},{"chapterId":"ch27-praise-real-progress","number":27,"title":"Praise Real Progress","readingTimeMinutes":14,"contentVariants":{"easy":{"summaryBullets":["Praise Real Progress asks the reader to see reinforcing improvement as a deliberate choice rather than a personality trait or lucky break.","The chapter argues that strong outcomes usually begin with a clearer reading of reward progress, because vague aims create waste and overreaction.","A repeated theme is that ignoring small gains often looks attractive in the short term, yet it weakens judgment when conditions become tense or uncertain.","The reader is pushed to notice how how people respond to progress can reveal more than loud claims, since incentives usually show up in patterns of behavior.","The chapter treats praise and credibility as a real balancing act, not a slogan, and it warns that pushing one side too far creates new vulnerabilities.","Instead of glorifying force or charisma, the material frames progress as the result of patient positioning, careful observation, and timely action.","A central lesson is that people around you respond to incentives, status, and perceived fairness, so your approach has to account for those forces.","The chapter highlights waiting for perfection before praising as a recurring mistake, especially for students and early career people who confuse intensity with leverage."],"takeaways":["reinforcing improvement","reward progress","how people respond to progress","praise and credibility","waiting for perfection before praising","respect without manipulation"],"practice":["Write the decision goal before you act","Name the incentive each side is responding to","Notice one signal that matters more than words","Check where waiting for perfection before praising could distort your judgment"]},"medium":{"summaryBullets":["Praise Real Progress asks the reader to see reinforcing improvement as a deliberate choice rather than a personality trait or lucky break.","The chapter argues that strong outcomes usually begin with a clearer reading of reward progress, because vague aims create waste and overreaction.","A repeated theme is that ignoring small gains often looks attractive in the short term, yet it weakens judgment when conditions become tense or uncertain.","The reader is pushed to notice how how people respond to progress can reveal more than loud claims, since incentives usually show up in patterns of behavior.","The chapter treats praise and credibility as a real balancing act, not a slogan, and it warns that pushing one side too far creates new vulnerabilities.","Instead of glorifying force or charisma, the material frames progress as the result of patient positioning, careful observation, and timely action.","A central lesson is that people around you respond to incentives, status, and perceived fairness, so your approach has to account for those forces.","The chapter highlights waiting for perfection before praising as a recurring mistake, especially for students and early career people who confuse intensity with leverage.","Progress praise becomes useful because it trains the reader to slow down and choose the next move with more intention.","The text emphasizes that trust and reputation are cumulative, meaning one impulsive win can undermine the long game if it damages legitimacy.","There is a strong 