lly for students and early career people who confuse intensity with leverage.","Progress praise becomes useful because it trains the reader to slow down and choose the next move with more intention.","The text emphasizes that trust and reputation are cumulative, meaning one impulsive win can undermine the long game if it damages legitimacy.","There is a strong distinction between reacting to appearances and understanding structure, because surface confidence often hides weak preparation.","The chapter argues that pressure should clarify priorities, not scramble them, and the best operators reduce noise before they escalate effort.","Another theme is that alliances, norms, and narratives shape outcomes as much as raw ability, especially inside schools, teams, and workplaces.","The reader is asked to think in terms of second order effects, asking what today’s move teaches others about your standards and intent.","Ethically, the chapter draws a line between strategic awareness and empty manipulation, stressing that durable influence depends on legitimacy.","By the end, relationship judgment is presented as a discipline of reading context well, acting with restraint, and preserving room for future moves."],"takeaways":["reinforcing improvement","reward progress","how people respond to progress","praise and credibility","waiting for perfection before praising","respect without manipulation","make people feel seen","progress"],"practice":["Write the decision goal before you act","Name the incentive each side is responding to","Notice one signal that matters more than words","Check where waiting for perfection before praising could distort your judgment","Choose a response that protects legitimacy","Review the tradeoff before making a public move","Ask what future behavior your choice will encourage","Keep a short note on what you learned from the outcome"]}},"examples":[{"exampleId":"ch27-ex01","title":"Friend tension","contexts":["personal"],"scenario":"A friend group starts drifting into small status games and mixed signals. You notice that people are reacting to how people respond to progress more than what anyone says directly, and the whole situation feels harder to read because everyone is trying to protect face at the same time.","whatToDo":["Use the chapter idea of reinforcing improvement by slowing the situation down, naming the actual goal, and responding in a way that protects the relationship while still dealing with the issue. Keep your move clear, proportionate, and consistent with the kind of reputation you want over time."],"whyItMatters":"Personal conflict in your twenties often gets worse because people chase short term relief instead of reading incentives and emotional stakes carefully. This example matters because it turns strategy into emotional maturity, showing how better judgment can reduce drama without turning every disagreement into a contest."},{"exampleId":"ch27-ex02","title":"Dating judgment","contexts":["personal"],"scenario":"You are trying to decide whether someone is trustworthy, but the attention and chemistry of the moment make it easy to ignore structure. The chapter’s focus on praise and credibility becomes relevant because attraction can hide weak incentives, unclear intentions, or unstable behavior.","whatToDo":["Apply the chapter by paying closer attention to repeated patterns, not isolated gestures. Look for whether words, incentives, and follow through line up, and choose a pace that gives you enough information to protect your standards without becoming cynical."],"whyItMatters":"A lot of personal regret comes from making large decisions while reading only mood and appearance. This scenario matters because it shows how strategic thinking can stay ethical and grounded, helping you build healthier relationships instead of reacting to intensity alone."},{"exampleId":"ch27-ex03","title":"Group project friction","contexts":["school"],"scenario":"A group project begins to stall because nobody wa