nal rather than reactive."],"whyItMatters":"Early career people are often judged not just on results but on how they think under pressure. This scenario matters because it turns the chapter into a workplace habit, showing how better judgment can build credibility before you have formal power."},{"exampleId":"ch33-ex06","title":"Team messaging","contexts":["work"],"scenario":"A team is about to send a strong message to a client, manager, or partner, but the internal discussion is split between sounding tough and sounding cooperative. The deeper issue is not wording alone. It is what the message signals about standards, leverage, and future expectations.","whatToDo":["Use the chapter idea of what specific praise reinforces to choose language that is firm, clear, and aligned with the outcome you actually want. Make sure the message sets the right incentive structure and does not create unnecessary contempt, confusion, or escalation."],"whyItMatters":"A lot of workplace influence comes from signals that travel beyond the immediate conversation. This example matters because it shows that communication is strategic design, not just expression, and that a good move should strengthen both results and legitimacy."}],"quiz":{"passingScorePercent":80,"questions":[{"questionId":"ch33-h-q01","prompt":"According to this chapter, what is the best starting point for using specific written appreciation well?","choices":["Escalating quickly so people take you seriously","Clarifying the real goal and reading the context carefully","Copying the strongest voice in the room","Trusting first impressions over patterns"],"correctIndex":1},{"questionId":"ch33-h-q02","prompt":"Why does the chapter warn against generic praise?","choices":["Because it creates fast learning","Because it looks disciplined to outsiders","Because it can feel effective early but usually weakens judgment later","Because it only works in school settings"],"correctIndex":2},{"questionId":"ch33-h-q03","prompt":"What doe